04755nam a22005895i 9780822390053DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223900537 a10.1515/97808223900532doi  a(DE-B1597)553755  a(OCoLC)1167247033  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBL313b.B54 2009 7aPOL0100002bisacsh1 aBoer, Roland, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitical Myth :bOn the Use and Abuse of Biblical Themes /cRoland Boer; ed. by Kenneth Surin, Philip Goodchild, Creston Davis. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (266 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Slant: Religion, Politics, Ontology : 3900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 Toward a Theory of Political Myth -- t2 Women First? On the Legacy of “Primitive Communism” -- t3 The Fantasy of Myth -- t4 The Sacred Economy -- t5 Foreign Policy and the Fantasy of Israel in Australia -- t6 Christianity, Capitalism, and the Fantasy of Israel in the United States -- t7 Mythmaking for the Left -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndexes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this provocative and necessary work, Roland Boer, a leading biblical scholar and cultural theorist, develops a political myth for the Left: a powerful narrative to be harnessed in support of progressive policy. Boer focuses on foundational stories in the Hexateuch, the first six books of the Bible, from Genesis through Joshua. He contends that the “primal story” that runs from Creation, through the Exodus, and to the Promised Land is a complex political myth, one that has been appropriated recently by the Right to advance reactionary political agendas. To reclaim it in support of progressive political ends, Boer maintains, it is necessary to understand the dynamics of political myth.Boer elaborates a theory of political myth in dialogue with Ernst Bloch, Theodor Adorno, Alain Badiou, Jacques Lacan, and Slavoj Žižek. Through close readings of well-known biblical stories he then scrutinizes the nature of political myth in light of feminism, psychoanalysis, and Marxism. Turning to contemporary politics, he examines the statements of prominent American and Australian politicians to show how the stories of Creation, conquest, Paradise, and the Promised Land have been distorted into a fantasy of Israel as a perpetual state in the making and a land in need of protection. Boer explains how this fantasy of Israel shapes U.S. and Australian foreign and domestic policies, and he highlights the links between it and the fantasy of unfettered global capitalism. Contending that political myths have repressed dimensions which if exposed undermine the myths’ authority, Boer urges the Left to expose the weakness in the Right’s mythos. He suggests that the Left make clear what the world would look like were the dream of unconstrained capitalism to be realized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBible and politics. 0aMyth in the Bible. 0aMythologyxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aDavis, Creston, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoodchild, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSurin, Kenneth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390053zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390053423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822390053/orig